	<body epub:type="backmatter">
		<section id="endnotes" epub:type="endnotes">
			<h2 epub:type="title">Endnotes</h2>
			<ol>
				<li id="note-1" epub:type="endnote">
					<p>Nicolas indeed declares of Adhelmar, earlier in the tale, in such high terms as are not uncommon to this chronicle:<br/>
					<i xml:lang="fr">Hardi estait et fier comme lions,<br/>
					Et si faisait balades et chançons,<br/>
					Rondeaulx et laiz, très bans et pleins de grâce,<br/>
					Comme Orpheus, cet menestrier de Thrace</i>.
					<a href="FILENAME.xhtml#noteref-1" epub:type="backlink">↩</a></p>
				</li>
				<li id="note-2" epub:type="endnote">
					<p>There is humor in his deposition that Gilles and Ysabeau and he were loitering before Saint Benoît’s in friendly discourse⁠—“<i xml:lang="es">pour soy esbatre</i>.” Perhaps René prompted this; but in itself, it is characteristic of Montcorbier that he trenched on perjury, blithely, in order to screen Ysabeau. <a href="FILENAME.xhtml#noteref-2" epub:type="backlink">↩</a></p>
				</li>
				<li id="note-3" epub:type="endnote">
					<p>TEXT <a href="FILENAME.xhtml#noteref-3" epub:type="backlink">↩</a></p>
				</li>
				<li id="note-2" epub:type="endnote">
					<p>TEXT <a href="FILENAME.xhtml#noteref-2" epub:type="backlink">↩</a></p>
				</li>
				<li id="note-2" epub:type="endnote">
					<p>TEXT <a href="FILENAME.xhtml#noteref-2" epub:type="backlink">↩</a></p>
				</li>
				<li id="note-2" epub:type="endnote">
					<p>TEXT <a href="FILENAME.xhtml#noteref-2" epub:type="backlink">↩</a></p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</section>
	</body>
</html>
